Although an open trade policy that allows for increasing flows in agricultural commodities is a good way to adapt to future climate impacts, certain caveats apply. Trade liberalization could have major consequences on the environment because increasing agricultural production in favorable locations could lead to additional GHG emissions, for example through deforestation, increased use of fertilizers, or intensified livestock production (
 
  13
 ). The link between trade liberalization and potential environmental impacts calls for a closer integration of trade and environmental policies in international negotiations (
 
  41
 ).
